First Glances: PASS urine biomarkers

Marshall Brown
3/20/2015

Introduction

A first look at the urine biomarker data where I summarize the data using descriptive statistics, provide simple visualizations of measurements over time, and apply some first steps to modeling biomarker values.

Sample sizes

Values are shown for data where biomarker information is known (and for the full data).

  • Number of participants: 1080 (1087)
  • Total number of measurements: 2745 (2819)
    • 57 individuals with one or more missing measurements.

Mixed effect models

  • fixed effects:

    • Time since diagnosis (non-linear)
    • Age

  • random effects

    • individual
    • Factor indicating whether measurements were taken within a year from diagnosis vs greater than a year from diagnosis**
    • random slope for age**

compare the expanded models to simpler models using ANOVA

  • Simpler models fit the data better.

Mixed effect models: PCA3

  • Marginal \( R^2 \): 0.07 Conditional \( R^2 \): 0.85
  • fixed: age, (non-linear) time from diagnosis
  Value Std.Error p-value
(Intercept) 1.5 0.24 <0.001
age 0.03 0.004 <0.001
ns(time)' 0.5 0.11 <0.001
ns(time)'' 1.4 0.23 <0.001
ns(time)''' 1.7 0.46 <.0001
  • random: individual effect
        (Intercept)  Residual
StdDev:   0.822       0.368

Modelling summary

  • Fixed effects are not good at explaining variation.
    • time from diagnosis is associated with both biomarkers.
    • age is associated with PCA3 but not TMPRSS2:ERG.
  • lots of individual level variation.
  PCA3 TMPRSS2:ERG
marginal \( R^2 \) 0.07 0.01
conditional \( R^2 \) 0.85 0.69

  • simpler models are better

  • more work to be done to determine if there are batch/site effects.

  • need to spend more time checking mixed model assumptions.
